        rdfs:comment        "In S. cerevisiae cells, the amino group of glutamate and the amide group of glutamine are the source of nitrogen for all other macromolecules |CITS: [1975578]|. In order to provide ammonia for the synthesis of glutamine during growth on glutamate-yielding nitrogen sources, cells degrade glutamate into ammonia. The main pathway for S. cerevisiae glutamate degradation is catalyzed by the NAD dependent glutamate dehydrogenase encoded by GDH2 |CITS:[1975578]|. Transcriptional regulation of GDH2 is dependent upon six different sequence elements present in the promoter |CITS:[1682801]|. Two elements behave as upstream activation sites (UAS) while the remaining four sites inhibit the effects of the two UASs |CITS: [1652057]|. One UAS has been shown to activate transcription during growth on nonfermentable carbon sources or on limiting amounts of glucose |CITS:[1652057]|. The other UAS is under the control of nitrogen catabolite repression (NCR) |CITS: [4394512]|. Under nitrogen-poor conditions, GDH2 expression is upregulated by the transcriptional activator Gln3p and the co-activator Hfi1p |CITS:[1990286]|, |CITS:[8416910]|, |CITS:[10048020]|. Conversely, in the presence of an optimal nitrogen source such as glutamine, GDH2 transcription is repressed by the transcription factor Ure2p |CITS:[1990286]|. Unrelated to NCR, GDH2 gene expression is regulated by ammonia concentrations. An increase in intracellular ammonia leads to a decrease in GDH2 expression |CITS:[12851403]| but an increase in extracellular ammonia leads to an increase in GDH2 transcription and Gdh2p activity |CITS:[7592450]|. Gdh2p enzyme activity also appears to be regulated by phosphorylation through cAMP-dependent and cAMP-independent protein kinases and subsequent proteolysis |CITS:[6319381]|, |CITS:[7009211]|." ;
        rdfs:label          "glutamate degradation IX" ;
